{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a4927a07-302b-4759-b6e9-f845c4eaf5c4","content":"On macOS, crash info is captured automatically by the OS:\n\n**Crash Reports (text-based, always generated):**\n- `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` — user processes\n- `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` — system processes\n\nLook for files named like `YourApp_<date>_<host>.ips`. You can also open **Console.app → Crash Reports** to browse them.\n\n**Core Dumps (binary, opt-in):**\n```bash\n# Enable core dumps for the current shell\nulimit -c unlimited\n# Re-run your app — core file goes to /cores/\n./MyApp\nls /cores/\n```\n\nCore dumps are disabled by default (`ulimit -c 0`). You must set `ulimit -c unlimited` **before** the crash occurs.\n\n**Tips:**\n- The `.ips` crash report includes the signal, faulting address, thread backtraces, and register state — often enough to diagnose the issue.\n- To analyze a core dump, use `lldb`:\n  ```bash\n  lldb ./MyApp -c /cores/core.<pid>\n  ```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"56e7d79e-35b9-4555-b321-a689db04823b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET application on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.\n\nOn macOS, when a process crashes, the OS automatically generates crash reports. Here's what I know:\n\n1. **macOS Crash Reports** are stored in `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (user-level) or `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (system-level).\n2. Core dumps can be enabled via `ulimit -c unlimited`, and they go to `/cores/`.\n\n\n3. I can also check Console.app to view and search through crash logs directly.\n\nLet me give a concise answer.","outputTokens":453,"requestId":"D7C7:260F1B:F6475D:11B753C:69F2B460"},"id":"669643b3-66a1-4a5f-ad6f-46aca6ab5dc4","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:48:37.311Z","parentId":"23c7f2a9-47f6-45f3-9515-77cc450d0935"}
